Class AssertLosslessJson

extends JSON
    JSON serializer/deserializer which asserts that deserialization is lossless (i.e. that the result can be serialized back to the same JSON).

      • isJsonDateEquals

        protected static boolean isJsonDateEquals(com.google.gson.JsonElement expected,
                                          com.google.gson.JsonElement actual)
        Checks if two JSON values are dates which are equal to the millisecond. This is used to accommodate differences due to date-time formatting and the limited precision of the Java7 time types.
        Parameters:
        expected - Expected JSON value.
        actual - Actual JSON value.
        Returns:
        true if expected and actual are date-time values which are equal to the millisecond.

      • assertJsonEquals

        public static void assertJsonEquals(com.google.gson.JsonElement expected,
                                    com.google.gson.JsonElement actual)
                             throws AssertionError
        Asserts that two JSON elements are equal. This function does not consider the order of properties in an object to be significant. It also does not consider differences in date values (strings which match the RFC 3339 date-time pattern) of less than 1 millisecond to be significant.
        Parameters:
        expected - The expected JSON element.
        actual - The actual JSON element.
        Throws:
        AssertionError - If actual is not equal to expected.
